  "prompt": "How much import duties would be applied over a clicker worth $2 from U.S.A to India?",
  "response": "Import duties on goods shipped from the U.S.A. to India depend on the classification of the item under India's Customs Tariff, the value of the item, and any applicable trade agreements or exemptions. For a \"clicker\" (assuming it\u2019s a small handheld device), here\u2019s how the process works:\n\n1. **Customs Tariff Classification**: The clicker would need to be classified under the appropriate Harmonized System (HS) code. For example, it might fall under HS Code **8517** (telecommunication devices) or **8543** (electrical machinery), depending on its function.\n\n2. **Applicable Duty Rate**: Once classified, the import duty rate would apply. For most electronic or mechanical devices, the basic customs duty (BCD) in India is **10-20%**, but it can vary. Additionally, **Integrated Goods and Services Tax (IGST)** is applied at **18%** on the total value (which includes the duty).\n\n3. **De Minimis Threshold**: India does not have a de minimis threshold for duty-free imports, meaning even low-value items are subject to duties and taxes.\n\n4. **Calculation Example**:\n   - Product value: $2 (approx. \u20b9166 at current exchange rates).\n   - Basic Customs Duty (BCD): Assume 10% \u2192 \u20b916.6.\n   - Total value after BCD: \u20b9166 + \u20b916.6 = \u20b9182.6.\n   - IGST (18% on \u20b9182.6): \u20b932.87.\n   - Total payable: \u20b916.6 (BCD) + \u20b932.87 (IGST) = \u20b949.47 (approx. $0.60).\n\n5. **Procedural Costs**: There may also be small handling or clearance fees charged by the shipping company or customs.\n\n**Note**: Actual duty may vary depending on the exact HS code, product description, and any exemptions or special rates. For precise details, consult a customs broker or the Indian Customs website.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
